                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Before I start with what I originally typed I'd like to say that yes I think the pvp system is horrible, no I don't think that soe will actually read this post and fix it because they are horrible, and no I have not nor will I ever buy eq2, but yes I'm still playing eq mostly due to habit and friends that I've met online but are slowly dwindling away to eq2 halo and wow and thus I'll eventually quit eq and go to wow or focus on other stuff with my spare time.  There's no need to read the rest of this text and say stuff about how everything's dead and I'm beating a dead horse that is dead.
<br />

<br />
The one thing I don't get is this. 
<br />

<br />
People complain about resists being too high - no spells landing so it all favors melees
<br />

<br />
SoE says "wow lets fix pvp"  and then changes it so that all spells land.
<br />

<br />
Two weeks later they figure out that's overpowering and change it back to the exact same thing it was earlier.
<br />

<br />
The big problem I see is that spells like root and slow  and mez (basically everything enchanters get) are too powerful when used without being resisted in pvp.  If I could slow the first try every time, and root too, I could take on about 5 pure melees assuming nukes landed too by just root/nuking them to death.
<br />

<br />
The reason I typed this was that I figured no one else has ever really said that nukes in particular, and maybe dots too, should be *very* hard to resist, and spells that put any sort of real lock on a character should be easier to resist.
<br />

<br />
Perhaps if they made it so that they left the 40% max nuke cap in, took out all the other crap so that nukes actually landed for full damage (since melees get extended range on their melee, the lowered effectiveness of ac, and the ability to melee instantly without stopping to cast on their side) and then guarantee that 30% of the nuke (50% for lures) will DEFINITELY land, and base the rest on resists.
<br />

<br />
Melees don't have to worry about casters being able to fully lock out all melee, so they can just stand there being melee'd for 0's and 5's nuking the monk/warrior/etc.. to death.  How is that prospect so ludicrous whereas a wizard using lures at the high end can't get some chars down to 90% health from full health during the course of a fight in which the wizard dies because he was trying to cast?  I saw one fight where a wizard cast 8 lures, and by the time he was done the monk he was fighting had lost a massive 9% health, and he cast the lures all over the course of 2 minutes or less.  I'd say more like 1 minute 30 seconds.  8 lures = 9% of someone's health?  if any real melee that can use a 2hander had 8 rounds of melee free on a wizard, the wizard would die, and unless (possibly even if) he's using a dathor, those rounds would be faster than the raw casting time of the lures, not including the spell refresh, the fizzles, the interrupts, etc.  It's horribly unbalanced (duh).  But if they did what I have suggested (which they won't do duh again) then the system would merit people that have high resists without making it so that you can shut someone out of a fight.  You should never come up against someone in almost equal gear, of the same level with the same number of aa's and then already essentially have the fight won.  The moment they made the fight completely about resists was the moment they killed high end caster pvp (go ahead and insert some witty quip like the moment they gave melees weapons was the moment they killed caster pvp, or the moment they made pvp was the moment they killed caster pvp if you want to, but I remember a brief period when pvp was fun).
<br />

<br />
fin.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
