                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Years ago I played a MMORPG where skill was the primary factor in PvP.  It was called Neverwinter Nights and ran on AOL.  (If you think UO was the first online graphical MMORPG you're mistaken) 
<br />

<br />
Skill was equally important in 1-on-1, group fights, and guild-vs-guild... although each of those needed somewhat different strategies.  There was plenty of randomness, one really bad saving throw could end the fight, but the more skilled would likely win, even when jumped, with lesser gear, with 30 percent less hit points.  It was just very strategic.
<br />

<br />
Everyone in PvP was the same class and level though because that class was just best in PvP (but not in PvE).  Occasionally someone could do well with a different class, but they'd be at a real disadvantage.
<br />

<br />
That game was cancelled at the height of its popularity for technical reasons.  But for awhile it proved how much a game really could support PvP, community, and roleplay.  Newer games have much better graphics, but they never learned from it in those other areas.  I bring this up just to prove that it IS possible to get it right, current games just haven't done it yet.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
